            {
                "s2_paper_id": "452bcc3ab75770cb0cccaee7fe06f0eef255ff63",
                "title": "8.2: Invited Paper: Amorphous Metal Thin\u2010Film Transistors: High Mobility TFT Fabricated by An All PVD Process",
                "year": 2021,
                "venue": "SID Symposium Digest of Technical Papers",
                "citation_count": 2,
                "reference_count": 3,
                "abstract": "Players across the display industry generally agree that developing innovative new technology is essential to survival. \u2018Innovate or die\u2019 is the new industry mantra in response to Generation 10 display fabs as one analyst put it [1]. Dongsheng Wang, past chairman of BOE Technology Group, embodied this philosophy in the \u201cSurvival Law\u201d [2]. However you state it, pushing the limits of display backplane devices is essential to meeting the demand for higher resolution, refresh rate, dynamic range, and flexibility. This work reports on a new type of thin-film transistor (TFT) that uses amorphous metal thin-films as the gate electrode to enable a thin gate dielectric and boost transistor mobility. Amorphous metals are known to be very strong and flexible, making these materials well suited for flexible electronic applications [3]. The transistors discussed in this work have been named Amorphous Metal Thin-Film Transistors; abbreviated to AMeTFT, to differentiate them from a traditional TFT, while hopefully avoiding confusion with Active Matrix TFT (AM-TFT), a term (acronym) that was once used in the LCD industry. The AMeTFT concept generally applies to any semiconductor, i.e. a-Si, low temperature polycrystalline silicon (LTPS), or oxide semiconductors (IGZO, SnO, ZnO, etc). This work reports on efforts to develop an IGZOAMeTFT, compatible with low temperature processing. The end goal being to create a flexible high-speed device useful for pixel control, as well as gate-on-array and potentially data-on-array applications. The data presented in this report is for an AMeTFT processed entirely using physical vapor deposition (PVD) methods. The amorphous metal gate as well as the source and drain electrodes were deposited using standard metal PVD process, whereas the gate insulator and oxide semiconductors were deposited using reactive sputter PVD. While the device data presented in this report is for AMeTFT fabricated on rigid glass substrates, the PVD processes used should enable transition to flexible substrates in the future.",
